T3 Code — Browser Automation
=============================

Portions of apps/server/src/browser/ are derived from GStack Browser, an MIT-
licensed project by Garry Tan:

    https://github.com/gstack/gstack
    Copyright (c) 2026 Garry Tan

GStack Browser provides the accessibility-tree + @ref element-selection system,
Playwright Chromium lifecycle management, anti-bot hardening, dialog handling,
and the per-command plaintext output format that this module reproduces.

The MIT license text is available at:
    https://github.com/gstack/gstack/blob/main/LICENSE

Vendoring approach
------------------

All files under apps/server/src/browser/core/ are **byte-identical to the
corresponding file under gstack/browse/src/** aside from a single 1-line
comment prepended at the top of every file identifying the origin. No logic,
imports, or identifiers have been modified. Diffs between any vendored file
and the upstream version are exactly +1 / -0 (the vendor-header line).

To run on Node.js without requiring the Bun runtime, we load
`core/bun-polyfill.cjs` at server startup (`--require`). That polyfill —
itself part of upstream gstack — provides `Bun.serve`, `Bun.spawn`,
`Bun.spawnSync`, and `Bun.sleep` backed by Node's `http` and `child_process`.
For the SQLite dependency used by `cookie-import-browser.ts`
(`import { Database } from 'bun:sqlite'`), T3's server runs under the Bun
runtime in production as well as dev — T3 already depends on
`@effect/sql-sqlite-bun` and `@types/bun`, so Bun is the natural runtime.

